You know, about...

231
00:22:40,277 --> 00:22:43,769
I almost forgot. I'm fine.

232
00:22:47,317 --> 00:22:48,477
Good.

233
00:22:49,853 --> 00:22:51,912
Because, you know, I was thinking...

234
00:22:51,988 --> 00:22:55,321
you didn't actually see,
all you did was hear.

235
00:22:56,026 --> 00:22:57,994
And you know what they say.

236
00:22:58,061 --> 00:23:00,928
- What?
- Seeing is believing.

237
00:23:01,498 --> 00:23:02,726
Not hearing.

238
00:23:04,134 --> 00:23:07,433
- What about Ingrid Bergman?
- Ingrid Bergman?

239
00:23:09,840 --> 00:23:12,673
Joan of Arc. She played Joan of Arc.

240
00:23:14,344 --> 00:23:15,743
Joan of Arc.

241
00:23:17,347 --> 00:23:21,477
Joan didn't see either.
She just heard, like me.

242
00:23:32,095 --> 00:23:33,289
<i>Jerry?</i>

243
00:23:37,567 --> 00:23:39,592
- Oh, God.
<i>- That's right.</i>

244
00:23:43,173 --> 00:23:45,437
- Is that you?
<i>- In person.</i>

245
00:23:48,278 --> 00:23:51,736
- You're not on the radio?
<i>- Have you got a radio out here?</i>

246
00:23:52,716 --> 00:23:54,343
- No.
<i>- Bingo.</i>

247
00:23:55,385 --> 00:23:56,443
You're here?

248
00:23:58,822 --> 00:24:01,450
- In my bathroom?
<i>- Come take a look.</i>

249
00:24:02,826 --> 00:24:07,286
- I can't. I'm naked.
<i>- You think I don't know what you've got?</i>

250
00:24:08,098 --> 00:24:10,896
That was another little goof of mine.
Shame.

251
00:24:11,434 --> 00:24:14,062
<i>I don't know why I thought we needed shame.</i>

252
00:24:15,138 --> 00:24:16,537
<i>Come on out.</i>

253
00:24:29,486 --> 00:24:31,010
<i>Don't catch cold.</i>

254
00:24:39,162 --> 00:24:41,153
Not what you expected?

255
00:24:47,604 --> 00:24:49,595
I picked a look you could understand.

256
00:24:49,673 --> 00:24:51,698
For someone else,
I would've looked different.

257
00:24:51,775 --> 00:24:55,973
I could do any face, voice, whatever.
I could even be a woman.

258
00:24:57,781 --> 00:25:01,410
- Feeling a little strange?
- Very strange.

259
00:25:01,618 --> 00:25:03,586
Like you're going to faint?

260
00:25:05,055 --> 00:25:07,182
You know what's good for that?

261
00:25:07,857 --> 00:25:08,857
Shaving.

262
00:25:10,293 --> 00:25:12,784
- Shaving?
- Sometimes when you don't feel normal...

263
00:25:12,862 --> 00:25:15,387
doing a normal thing makes you feel normal.

264
00:25:15,465 --> 00:25:16,659
Here, start shaving.

265
00:25:35,685 --> 00:25:36,982
Go ahead.

266
00:25:37,320 --> 00:25:38,320
I am.

267
00:25:38,388 --> 00:25:39,946
I don't mean with the shaving...

268
00:25:40,023 --> 00:25:42,651
with the questions
that are popping into your head.

269
00:25:45,095 --> 00:25:46,153
Yeah.

270
00:25:48,832 --> 00:25:51,323
- Why me?
- Why not you?

271
00:25:52,602 --> 00:25:54,194
You mean, there's no special...

272
00:25:54,271 --> 00:25:58,105
Life is a crap shoot, like the millionth
customer who crosses a bridge...

273
00:25:58,174 --> 00:26:00,404
gets to shake hands with the governor.

274
00:26:00,644 --> 00:26:03,613
You thought I picked you
because you're better than everybody?

275
00:26:03,680 --> 00:26:04,680
I'm not?

276
00:26:04,748 --> 00:26:07,046
You're better than some,
but not as good as others.

277
00:26:07,117 --> 00:26:09,347
But you crossed the bridge
at the right time.

278
00:26:09,419 --> 00:26:14,186
If you wanted to see me,
why didn't you just appear over my bed?

279
00:26:15,392 --> 00:26:17,917
Hollywood. Next question.

280
00:26:24,534 --> 00:26:29,233
People are always praying to you.
Do you listen?

281
00:26:30,073 --> 00:26:33,008
I can't help hearing. I don't always listen.

282
00:26:33,476 --> 00:26:36,206
- Then you don't care?
- Of course I care.

283
00:26:36,579 --> 00:26:38,945
I care plenty. But what can I do?

284
00:26:39,015 --> 00:26:41,006
What can you do?

285
00:26:41,885 --> 00:26:42,909
You're God.

286
00:26:42,986 --> 00:26:46,217
Only for the big picture.
I don't get into details.

287
00:26:46,289 --> 00:26:48,757
Then whatever happens to us...

288
00:26:48,858 --> 00:26:51,656
Happens. Here, I put in a new blade.

289
00:26:53,296 --> 00:26:55,696
You mean, there's no plan...

290
00:26:55,765 --> 00:26:59,030
no scheme to guide our destinies?

291
00:27:00,003 --> 00:27:04,133
- A lot of it is luck.
- Luck? Just luck?

292
00:27:05,942 --> 00:27:09,207
Put on a little toilet paper.
I'll get you a piece.

293
00:27:12,682 --> 00:27:17,085
- You don't control our lives?
- I gave you a world and everything in it.

294
00:27:17,654 --> 00:27:19,451
It's all up to you.

295
00:27:19,522 --> 00:27:24,391
- But we need help.
- That's why I gave you each other. Here.

296
00:27:26,563 --> 00:27:30,260
With your powers,
you could solve so many problems.

297
00:27:31,634 --> 00:27:33,067
Don't wet it.

298
00:27:34,437 --> 00:27:36,564
- Are you sure?
- Am I sure?

299
00:27:37,107 --> 00:27:39,473
Did I do a good job on the Grand Canyon?

300
00:27:42,679 --> 00:27:47,275
Anyway, why don't you?
Solve all our problems.

301
00:27:47,484 --> 00:27:51,648
- Work a few miracles.
- I don't do miracles. They're too flashy.

302
00:27:51,988 --> 00:27:54,047
And they upset the natural balance.

303
00:27:54,824 --> 00:27:57,657
No miracles? I knew it.

304
00:27:58,661 --> 00:28:01,494
Maybe now and then,
just to keep my hand in.

305
00:28:01,564 --> 00:28:04,829
The last miracle I did was the 1969 Mets.

306
00:28:06,002 --> 00:28:08,732
Before that,
I think you have to go back to the Red Sea.

307
00:28:09,172 --> 00:28:10,696
That was a beauty.

308
00:28:11,508 --> 00:28:14,671
No offense,
but I don't believe the Red Sea...

309
00:28:14,744 --> 00:28:17,907
and I don't believe
six days to create the world.

310
00:28:18,114 --> 00:28:19,445
You're right.

311
00:28:19,783 --> 00:28:21,444
- I am?
- Tell you the truth...

312
00:28:21,518 --> 00:28:25,215
I thought about it for five days
and did the whole job in one.

313
00:28:25,288 --> 00:28:27,153
I'm really best under pressure.

314
00:28:27,991 --> 00:28:32,587
- One day to create the world?
- And the sun. I hate to work in the dark.

315
00:28:33,062 --> 00:28:34,427
You have to remember...

316
00:28:34,497 --> 00:28:37,796
that one of my days
is not exactly one of yours.

317
00:28:37,867 --> 00:28:38,891
How long are they?

318
00:28:38,968 --> 00:28:42,404
When I got up this morning,
Sigmund Freud was still in medical school.

319
00:28:49,379 --> 00:28:52,177
- If you're so involved with us...
- Yeah?

320
00:28:52,615 --> 00:28:56,016
How can you permit all the suffering
that goes on in the world?

321
00:28:57,287 --> 00:28:59,778
- How can I permit the suffering?
- Yeah.

322
00:28:59,856 --> 00:29:02,347
I don't permit the suffering. You do.

323
00:29:02,425 --> 00:29:05,326
Free will. All the choices are yours.

324
00:29:05,662 --> 00:29:08,096
Choices? What choices?

325
00:29:08,331 --> 00:29:12,700
You can love, cherish and nurture
each other, or you can kill each other.

326
00:29:12,769 --> 00:29:16,671
Incidentally, "kill" is the word.
It's not "waste."

327
00:29:17,140 --> 00:29:20,667
If I meant "waste," I would have written,
"Thou shalt not waste."

328
00:29:20,743 --> 00:29:23,473
You're doing some very funny things
with words here.

329
00:29:23,546 --> 00:29:28,347
You're also turning the sky into mud.
I look down, I don't believe the filth.

330
00:29:28,818 --> 00:29:32,379
Using rivers for toilets,
poisoning my fishes.

331
00:29:33,223 --> 00:29:37,455
You want a miracle?
You make a fish from scratch. You can't.

332
00:29:37,727 --> 00:29:41,788
You think only God can make a tree?
Try coming up with a mackerel.

333
00:29:42,332 --> 00:29:44,994
And when the last one is gone,
that'll be that.

334
00:29:45,134 --> 00:29:50,128
Eighty-six on the fishes. Good-bye, sky.
So long, world. Over and out.

335
00:29:50,640 --> 00:29:54,701
- I thought you said we would make it.
- I said, you have to make it work.

336
00:29:55,512 --> 00:29:57,844
- You don't care.
- I do care.

337
00:29:58,081 --> 00:30:02,711
- Then do something about it.
- I did. I got you to carry the ball.

338
00:30:05,088 --> 00:30:10,048
- I got no ball. How can I carry it?
- I gave you a mouth, didn't I?

339
00:30:10,560 --> 00:30:13,154
Tell people how I feel, what I said.

340
00:30:14,697 --> 00:30:16,062
How do I do that?

341
00:30:16,132 --> 00:30:18,566
How did you get to be an assistant manager?

342
00:30:18,635 --> 00:30:21,627
Did you ever hear of newspapers, reporters?

343
00:30:22,105 --> 00:30:26,269
You got a scoop here, an exclusive,
a hold-the-presses.

344
00:30:26,709 --> 00:30:27,767
Fine.

345
00:30:29,979 --> 00:30:33,779
And how do I convince anybody
that I've actually seen you?

346
00:30:33,850 --> 00:30:36,546
- That you exist?
- Simple.

347
00:30:39,122 --> 00:30:40,282
Show them this.

348
00:30:51,534 --> 00:30:55,630
- Your card?
- No, it's not my card. It's God's card.

349
00:30:56,539 --> 00:30:58,632
- It's God's card?
- Look at it.

350
00:30:59,042 --> 00:31:00,168
I am.

351
00:31:01,377 --> 00:31:04,608
- Do you know where I got it?
- At a novelty store?

352
00:31:05,848 --> 00:31:08,248
- God gave it to me.
- Did he?

353
00:31:09,319 --> 00:31:14,222
- May I ask when and where you got it?
- This morning, in my bathroom.

354
00:31:15,325 --> 00:31:17,953
God visited you in your bathroom
this morning?

355
00:31:18,027 --> 00:31:19,153
Yes.

356
00:31:20,463 --> 00:31:22,795
Sounds crazy to you, doesn't it?

357
00:31:23,232 --> 00:31:26,224
Yesterday,
he was just a voice on an intercom...

358
00:31:26,302 --> 00:31:28,532
and then he was on the radio.

359
00:31:28,938 --> 00:31:31,839
- God spoke to you on the radio?
- In my car.

360
00:31:32,008 --> 00:31:33,703
- What station?
- All stations.

361
00:31:33,776 --> 00:31:38,270
Right. And then this morning,
he showed up in your bathroom?

362
00:31:38,681 --> 00:31:39,739
Yes.

363
00:31:40,183 --> 00:31:44,779
Why do you suppose
the Almighty spoke to you, Mr...

364
00:31:44,854 --> 00:31:46,845
- Landers.
- Mr. Landers.

365
00:31:46,923 --> 00:31:51,326
Jerry Landers. He said that he wanted
me to be his messenger, like Moses.

366
00:31:53,396 --> 00:31:56,388
What sort of work do you do, Mr. Landers?

367
00:31:56,466 --> 00:31:59,401
I'm the assistant manager
of Food World in Burbank.

368
00:31:59,569 --> 00:32:03,528
I see. Then you don't speak
to God every day.

369
00:32:04,207 --> 00:32:06,107
Never before yesterday.

370
00:32:09,712 --> 00:32:14,547
Did God say why he needed a messenger...

371
00:32:14,617 --> 00:32:19,281
- at this particular time, Mr. Landers?
- Yes, he was very specific.

372
00:32:19,689 --> 00:32:22,954
He said that he wanted us to know
that it can work.

373
00:32:25,428 --> 00:32:28,090
- What "it" is that?
- Us "it."

374
00:32:28,464 --> 00:32:31,797
Our lives, our world, everything.

375
00:32:32,402 --> 00:32:37,135
He says that he's given us everything
that we need, and it's entirely up to us.

376
00:32:37,273 --> 00:32:41,266
- And those were his exact words?
- Close enough. You can print that.

377
00:32:41,377 --> 00:32:44,938
Did God specify the <i>Los Angeles Times</i>?

378
00:32:45,915 --> 00:32:47,746
That was my idea.

379
00:32:48,584 --> 00:32:50,609
Well, we're very grateful.

380
00:32:52,221 --> 00:32:53,347
I'm not a nut.

381
00:32:54,457 --> 00:32:57,290
- I didn't say that you were.
- I'm not even religious.

382
00:32:57,794 --> 00:33:01,423
Yes, thank you very much, Mr. Landers,
for bringing us this story.

383
00:33:01,497 --> 00:33:03,522
Look, don't brush me off.

384
00:33:04,467 --> 00:33:08,335
Do me a favor, and look at that card again.
Take a good hard look at it.

385
00:33:08,705 --> 00:33:09,933
Certainly.

386
00:33:12,642 --> 00:33:16,373
Now, does that look like something
I'd get at a novelty shop?

387
00:33:16,813 --> 00:33:17,871
Yes.

388
00:33:36,065 --> 00:33:39,660
Norman, did you just put a bag of potatoes
on top of that white bread?

389
00:33:39,736 --> 00:33:41,033
No, sir.

390
00:33:46,309 --> 00:33:49,642
- I think you did.
<i>- Mr, Landers, please come to Aisle 10.</i>

391
00:33:49,712 --> 00:33:51,407
<i>Aisle 10, please.</i>

392
00:33:52,749 --> 00:33:53,875
Did you hear that, Norman?

393
00:33:53,950 --> 00:33:56,714
Yes, never put a bag of potatoes
on top of a white bread.

394
00:33:56,786 --> 00:33:59,414
No, the page. I was just paged.
Did you hear that?

395
00:33:59,489 --> 00:34:02,253
I didn't hear anything. Did I?

396
00:34:04,260 --> 00:34:07,718
We'll get you a new white bread, ma'am.
Take care of it.

397
00:34:13,369 --> 00:34:14,461
God?

398
00:34:15,338 --> 00:34:19,672
Chemicals, all chemicals.
Turning kids into garbage cans.

399
00:34:20,710 --> 00:34:23,679
Jerry, I didn't see one word
in the newspapers.

400
00:34:23,746 --> 00:34:25,043
Of course not.

401
00:34:25,114 --> 00:34:28,606
That guy at the <i>Times</i> kept looking
at me like I was some kind of lunatic.

402
00:34:28,684 --> 00:34:29,878
And I felt like one.

403
00:34:31,821 --> 00:34:34,221
- Did you show him my card?
- Sure I did.

404
00:34:34,290 --> 00:34:37,748
And he said, "You can get one of those
in any novelty store."

405
00:34:38,127 --> 00:34:43,121
Here. You know, I really felt like an idiot.
Please, don't do that to me again.

406
00:34:45,368 --> 00:34:47,802
- You said what I said?
- Absolutely.

407
00:34:48,070 --> 00:34:51,062
And they didn't find God's word
fit to print?

408
00:34:51,974 --> 00:34:53,942
Some tough cookies, boy.

409
00:34:54,076 --> 00:34:55,668
- Did you get the Coke?
- Yes.

410
00:34:55,745 --> 00:34:57,406
I have Cup-a-Soup.

411
00:35:00,383 --> 00:35:02,078
- Good morning, Mrs. Levin.
- Hi.

412
00:35:02,151 --> 00:35:04,051
- Mrs. Green.
- Hi, Jerry.

413
00:35:04,487 --> 00:35:07,012
You know, I'd like you to meet...

414
00:35:12,328 --> 00:35:14,489
- You did it to me again.
- What'd she do?

415
00:35:16,399 --> 00:35:17,525
What?

416
00:35:19,202 --> 00:35:20,567
Nothing.

417
00:35:21,170 --> 00:35:23,161
- Can I help you ladies?
- No.

418
00:35:23,239 --> 00:35:25,867
- We're all right.
- Yes, thank you.

419
00:35:27,610 --> 00:35:30,204
- What was that all about?
- I don't know.

420
00:35:35,351 --> 00:35:38,809
- Why did you change on me?
- Why did you start to introduce me?

421
00:35:38,888 --> 00:35:41,049
I don't want to be
the only guy in the world...

422
00:35:41,123 --> 00:35:44,092
Look, I can't make appearances all over.
Don't you understand?

423
00:35:44,160 --> 00:35:47,527
- No, I don't.
- People would drop dead from hysterics.

424
00:35:47,663 --> 00:35:50,063
- Mr. Landers?
- This place is too busy.

425
00:35:50,299 --> 00:35:52,426
Can you sign this, please?

426
00:35:53,736 --> 00:35:54,828
<i>Jerry?</i>

427
00:35:56,739 --> 00:35:57,739
<i>Up here.</i>

428
00:35:58,941 --> 00:36:02,104
<i>- Let's go for a ride.</i>
- I'll meet you.

429
00:36:02,178 --> 00:36:04,806
- Where?
- What? Not you.

430
00:36:13,222 --> 00:36:17,249
I can't understand it. Why wouldn't
a religious editor believe you?

431
00:36:17,460 --> 00:36:21,021
Face it, you goofed again,
just like the avocado pit.

432
00:36:21,330 --> 00:36:23,321
You picked the wrong message boy.

433
00:36:23,399 --> 00:36:26,334
- You don't believe I'm here, do you?
- No, I don't.

434
00:36:27,036 --> 00:36:29,869
Then how do you explain
this conversation we're having?

435
00:36:29,939 --> 00:36:32,373
I'm having. I'm dreaming you.

436
00:36:32,842 --> 00:36:35,902
And I ought to be real glad
when I wake up, too.

437
00:36:36,312 --> 00:36:38,212
What color are my eyes?

438
00:36:39,081 --> 00:36:40,309
My eyes?

439
00:36:42,084 --> 00:36:43,176
Blue.

440
00:36:43,452 --> 00:36:44,714
My shirt?

441
00:36:45,321 --> 00:36:48,085
Red plaid.
What does that got to do with anything?

442
00:36:48,157 --> 00:36:50,591
- Do you dream in color?
- No.

443
00:36:50,660 --> 00:36:52,059
Bingo, again.

444
00:36:53,195 --> 00:36:55,527
Okay. All right.

445
00:36:56,766 --> 00:36:58,256
You know a lot of things...

446
00:36:58,334 --> 00:37:00,495
and you've been making things happen...

447
00:37:00,569 --> 00:37:01,866
but none of it seems...

448
00:37:01,938 --> 00:37:04,304
- Godlike?
- Yeah. Godlike.

449
00:37:04,407 --> 00:37:06,375
Now, what, to you, would be Godlike?

450
00:37:10,279 --> 00:37:12,907
- Change the weather.
- Special effects?

451
00:37:14,517 --> 00:37:18,283
What would you like?
A little earthquake? Small hurricane?

452
00:37:18,521 --> 00:37:20,921
No, I wouldn't want anybody hurt.

453
00:37:21,557 --> 00:37:24,822
I was just thinking, maybe,
what about a little rain?

454
00:37:25,094 --> 00:37:27,688
- Little rain?
- Yeah. A small shower.

455
00:37:28,297 --> 00:37:30,458
One small shower. You got it.

456
00:37:36,072 --> 00:37:37,539
It's raining.

457
00:37:38,574 --> 00:37:40,201
You made it rain.

458
00:37:41,177 --> 00:37:43,907
You didn't even bat an eye.
You didn't lift a finger.

459
00:37:43,980 --> 00:37:47,279
- Rain's not that hard.
- It's unbelievable.

460
00:37:47,350 --> 00:37:50,319
- Would you like it to rain a little harder?
- No, this is fine.

461
00:37:50,386 --> 00:37:53,116
- How about bigger drops?
- No. This is fine.

462
00:37:53,189 --> 00:37:55,555
Would you care for a little snow?

463
00:37:55,758 --> 00:37:57,089
I don't believe it.

464
00:38:01,364 --> 00:38:04,663
It's not raining outside. It's just in here.

465
00:38:05,034 --> 00:38:07,332
Why should I spoil everybody's day?

466
00:38:08,504 --> 00:38:10,995
- This is fantastic.
- Thank you.

467
00:38:11,207 --> 00:38:15,337
- It's just like Noah's ark.
- Same thing, without the smell.

468
00:38:45,107 --> 00:38:49,066
- What's the problem, officer?
- I was about to ask you.

469
00:38:52,014 --> 00:38:55,643
My radiator must be leaking.
I'm sorry about that.

470
00:39:03,059 --> 00:39:05,789
A radiator doesn't hold that much water.

471
00:39:08,697 --> 00:39:12,895
I must have driven through a car wash
with my windows open?

472
00:39:15,438 --> 00:39:17,099
- That'd do it.
- Yeah.

473
00:39:19,275 --> 00:39:23,006
- Roll up the windows next time.
- Yes, sir, I will. Yes, sir.

474
00:39:23,779 --> 00:39:25,337
Thank you, sir.

475
00:39:32,988 --> 00:39:37,220
- He believed that dumb excuse.
- There's an aura of goodness around you.

476
00:39:38,160 --> 00:39:39,218
You.

477
00:39:40,096 --> 00:39:42,894
Going to try a little harder
to get the word out?

478
00:39:45,034 --> 00:39:48,470
- Yeah! I'll give it another shot!
- That's my boy.

479
00:39:49,071 --> 00:39:50,470
Mr. Briggs.

480
00:39:51,674 --> 00:39:53,699
- You're all wet.
- Of course I'm wet.

481
00:39:53,776 --> 00:39:56,973
I didn't dry myself, I wanted you
to see this. Do you remember me?

482
00:39:57,046 --> 00:40:00,709
Of course. You're the nonbeliever
who spoke to God, twice, I believe.

483
00:40:00,783 --> 00:40:02,045
Four times, now.

484
00:40:02,118 --> 00:40:05,815
- Is he still visiting you in the toilet?
- I just rode with him in my car.

485
00:40:05,888 --> 00:40:07,651
This time, I have got the proof.

486
00:40:07,723 --> 00:40:11,955
- He gave you another calling card?
- No. He made it rain inside the car.

487
00:40:12,294 --> 00:40:15,422
This water that I'm dripping all over here
is water that he made.

488
00:40:15,831 --> 00:40:17,298
This is holy water.

489
00:40:18,801 --> 00:40:22,703
- If you'll excuse me, I really am in a hurry.
- I will not excuse you, Mr. Briggs!

490
00:40:22,771 --> 00:40:24,864
You are a reporter of religious events...

491
00:40:24,940 --> 00:40:28,398
and this is the most important
religious event of our time.

492
00:40:28,477 --> 00:40:30,138
And I expect you...

493
00:40:30,346 --> 00:40:33,144
I don't expect, I insist,
that you print his message...

494
00:40:33,215 --> 00:40:35,979
in your paper and give it
the prominence it deserves.

495
00:40:36,051 --> 00:40:38,611
Or, by God, you'll hear from me again.

496
00:40:40,623 --> 00:40:41,749
Jerry.

497
00:40:44,326 --> 00:40:45,918
No, listen to this.

498
00:40:46,095 --> 00:40:49,929
"It should come as no surprise to anyone
that in these tense-filled times...

499
00:40:49,999 --> 00:40:51,967
"religious freaks abound.

500
00:40:52,034 --> 00:40:54,832
"From the Bronx cabbie who claims
he drove Mary Magdalene...

501
00:40:54,904 --> 00:40:57,304
"to the airport last
Christmas..." Listen.

502
00:40:57,373 --> 00:40:59,898
"To the Burbank, California,
supermarket manager...

503
00:40:59,975 --> 00:41:03,809
"who insists he has had
four conversations with God, no less."

504
00:41:03,879 --> 00:41:04,971
What?

505
00:41:05,047 --> 00:41:06,912
"According to this second gentleman...

506
00:41:06,982 --> 00:41:10,349
"who flashes a calling card
with God's name on it...

507
00:41:10,653 --> 00:41:12,746
"God wants very much for us to know...

508
00:41:12,821 --> 00:41:16,416
"He is alive and well and that
our world can work. It's up to us."

509
00:41:16,492 --> 00:41:18,050
Let me see that.

510
00:41:18,894 --> 00:41:20,623
The <i>Los Angeles Times</i>.

511
00:41:21,463 --> 00:41:23,590
- Where is it?
- How could you, for God's...

512
00:41:23,666 --> 00:41:26,499
It's right here, with some terrific company.

513
00:41:26,735 --> 00:41:30,535
See this? A janitor who sleeps all night
tied up on a cross.

514
00:41:31,106 --> 00:41:33,131
Did anybody else say they saw God?

515
00:41:33,209 --> 00:41:37,612
No, but there's an insurance salesman
selling life-after-death policies.

516
00:41:38,214 --> 00:41:43,208
But only you have talked to the Big Boss.
Did you just say that you saw him?

517
00:41:44,520 --> 00:41:46,715
- Yes.
- You didn't just hear him?

518
00:41:47,289 --> 00:41:50,349
One line. That's all
they gave it is one line.

519
00:41:50,426 --> 00:41:54,021
- Are you saying now that you saw God?
- Three times, yeah.

520
00:41:54,563 --> 00:41:59,364
- Three times?
- In the bathroom, at work, and in the car.

521
00:42:01,203 --> 00:42:04,730
One lousy line. I don't believe it.

522
00:42:13,616 --> 00:42:16,244
Let's go away for a couple days, okay?

523
00:42:16,485 --> 00:42:21,320
- Bobbie, I know how crazy this all sounds.
- No, you don't.

524
00:42:25,894 --> 00:42:28,692
I saw him. He spoke to me.

525
00:42:30,633 --> 00:42:33,830
All right, let's say, for a minute,
that you saw God...

526
00:42:33,902 --> 00:42:36,962
Look, don't humor me.
That'll really make me crazy.

527
00:42:37,039 --> 00:42:39,803
Okay! You saw him.

528
00:42:40,976 --> 00:42:43,843
- But why is he talking to you?
- Why not me?

529
00:42:44,480 --> 00:42:47,608
Why not the Pope, or Billy Graham,
or somebody way up there?

530
00:42:47,683 --> 00:42:50,811
- He doesn't care about religion.
- God doesn't care about religion?

531
00:42:50,886 --> 00:42:52,080
That's what he said.

532
00:42:52,221 --> 00:42:55,952
He sure picked a funny business
to go into then, didn't he?

533
00:43:02,097 --> 00:43:03,530
I'm sorry, Jerry.

534
00:43:11,140 --> 00:43:14,166
I can't seem to accept the concept of you...

535
00:43:14,243 --> 00:43:18,577
actually having a real, honest-to-God
conversation with God.

536
00:43:19,214 --> 00:43:22,945
I don't understand
why he wanted to talk to you.

537
00:43:26,088 --> 00:43:29,854
God, listen to me, this whole thing
is making me nuts now, too.

538
00:43:30,159 --> 00:43:31,183
Too?

539
00:43:31,727 --> 00:43:34,560
- You do think I'm crazy.
- No.

540
00:43:36,732 --> 00:43:38,757
I don't think you're crazy.

541
00:43:39,535 --> 00:43:41,833
Which is why I think I'm crazy.

542
00:43:43,038 --> 00:43:46,667
Bobbie, how can I convince anyone at all,
if I can't convince you?

543
00:43:49,411 --> 00:43:53,142
Jerry, for some reason
that I can't even begin to fathom...

544
00:43:53,382 --> 00:43:56,476
you really believe all this stuff,
don't you?

545
00:43:58,120 --> 00:43:59,144
Can't you?

546
00:44:04,960 --> 00:44:06,427
I believe...

547
00:44:07,496 --> 00:44:08,963
that you believe.

548
00:44:10,099 --> 00:44:14,331
Which, in some sense,
is the same as believing, I guess, isn't it?

549
00:44:20,876 --> 00:44:23,140
Do you understand what I've said?

550
00:44:24,780 --> 00:44:26,805
Do you have any questions?

551
00:44:30,486 --> 00:44:31,646
Adam?

552
00:44:34,590 --> 00:44:36,683
Sounds pretty bananas, Dad.

553
00:44:44,533 --> 00:44:45,795
Hello?

554
00:44:45,968 --> 00:44:46,992
Who?

555
00:44:47,836 --> 00:44:49,997
No, he isn't home right now.

556
00:44:51,940 --> 00:44:53,635
No, that's not him.

557
00:44:54,476 --> 00:44:57,070
Yes, you can print that in your paper.

558
00:44:57,146 --> 00:44:59,774
He is definitely not the man
in the <i>Times</i> today.

559
00:44:59,948 --> 00:45:02,473
- Can I go now, Dad?
- Sure, Son.

560
00:45:04,019 --> 00:45:05,509
I'll meet you.

561
00:45:06,288 --> 00:45:09,815
Look, I'm his wife. You can believe me.
Don't call back.

562
00:45:33,782 --> 00:45:37,741
- What do you think?
- Maybe he's going through a stage.

563
00:45:38,353 --> 00:45:40,218
You know, "mentalpause."

564
00:45:40,556 --> 00:45:42,217
That's "menopause."

565
00:45:42,391 --> 00:45:45,292
- Yeah, like Grandma.
- I hope.

566
00:45:48,063 --> 00:45:49,655
<i>And finally, this note.</i>

567
00:45:49,731 --> 00:45:53,758
<i>The</i> Los Angeles Sunday Times <i>reports</i>
<i>today that in Tarzana, California...</i>

568
00:45:53,836 --> 00:45:57,363
<i>a supermarket manager, Jerry Landers,
had an alleged conversation...</i>

569
00:45:57,439 --> 00:45:59,532
<i>with someone he claimed was God.</i>

570
00:45:59,608 --> 00:46:02,634
<i>According to the story,
God has appeared on earth to reaffirm...</i>

571
00:46:02,711 --> 00:46:06,169
<i>that He lives and our world can work.
It's up to us.</i>

572
00:46:07,716 --> 00:46:11,015
<i>This reporter would like to hedge his bets
on the outside chance...</i>

573
00:46:11,086 --> 00:46:15,523
<i>that God did make this appearance
and that he just might be tuned to ABC.</i>

574
00:46:15,591 --> 00:46:17,923
<i>We'd like him to know, we did report it.</i>

575
00:46:17,993 --> 00:46:20,655
<i>This is Jerry Dunphy.
Thank you and good night.</i>

576
00:46:23,665 --> 00:46:28,432
- Even Moses didn't give his last name.
- That should get the phone ringing.

577
00:46:35,511 --> 00:46:36,535
I told you.

578
00:46:40,048 --> 00:46:41,276
Hello.

579
00:46:42,217 --> 00:46:45,618
Yes, this is Jerry Landers.
It's the <i>Tarzana Daily Review</i>.

580
00:46:46,555 --> 00:46:48,113
Yes, I'm the one.

581
00:46:48,757 --> 00:46:50,816
Spoke with him? Absolutely.

582
00:46:51,960 --> 00:46:54,656
About 6 foot, blondish hair...

583
00:46:56,298 --> 00:46:57,458
Oh, him.

584
00:46:58,667 --> 00:47:01,534
About 5' 7", I guess. Gray hair.

585
00:47:01,737 --> 00:47:04,103
- I almost forgot my project.
- Jerry.

586
00:47:04,172 --> 00:47:07,005
- I'm coming!
- You made the front page.

587
00:47:07,309 --> 00:47:08,503
What?

588
00:47:11,947 --> 00:47:14,040
- Everybody, look.
- What?

589
00:47:17,219 --> 00:47:20,188
Channel 11? That's the 10:00 news.

590
00:47:23,959 --> 00:47:27,952
- Can we stay up and watch us?
- Jerry, I don't want the kids on TV.

591
00:47:28,330 --> 00:47:30,764
Can't be any worse than watching it.

592
00:47:31,033 --> 00:47:33,558
Don't worry. Come on, kids.

593
00:47:34,536 --> 00:47:36,094
<i>Hold the cameras.</i>

594
00:47:38,740 --> 00:47:40,799
<i>- Mr, Landers?
- Yes.</i>

595
00:47:40,909 --> 00:47:42,809
<i>Channel 11, 10:00 news.</i>

596
00:47:43,145 --> 00:47:46,205
<i>You're quoted as saying
that you've talked with God, sir?</i>

597
00:47:46,281 --> 00:47:47,111
<i>Yes.</i>

598
00:47:47,182 --> 00:47:49,150
<i>- Face to face?
- That's right.</i>

599
00:47:49,217 --> 00:47:50,514
He's a fruitcake.

600
00:47:50,586 --> 00:47:55,114
<i>And you say God wants to affirm he's alive
and he's very disappointed...</i>

601
00:47:55,190 --> 00:47:59,149
<i>- with the way we're handling our world?
- That's right.</i>

602
00:48:00,095 --> 00:48:02,996
<i>How are you going to get people
to believe you?</i>

603
00:48:03,098 --> 00:48:05,225
<i>It wasn't my idea.</i>

604
00:48:05,767 --> 00:48:07,792
<i>He picked me.</i>

605
00:48:08,270 --> 00:48:12,764
Is God going to reveal himself to you,
as you claim he has?

606
00:48:13,308 --> 00:48:15,936
Not as I claim he has. As he has.

607
00:48:17,045 --> 00:48:22,005
I don't know if he'll show up again,
but he gave me his message and...

608
00:48:22,117 --> 00:48:24,745
- Dad. It's 10 to.
- Yes, Adam.

609
00:48:25,988 --> 00:48:27,285
That he exists?

610
00:48:27,356 --> 00:48:31,315
Yes, and that he would like us
to cherish and nurture each other...

611
00:48:31,393 --> 00:48:34,487
<i>- as opposed to killing one another.
- He said that?</i>

612
00:48:35,297 --> 00:48:39,529
<i>Yeah, that he's our shepherd,
and we shall not want.</i>

613
00:48:40,502 --> 00:48:43,471
<i>- We can quote you?
- I didn't make that up.</i>

614
00:48:45,507 --> 00:48:50,501
<i>For 10:00 news, this is Mario Machado
and the man who talked to God in Tarzana.</i>

615
00:48:52,447 --> 00:48:55,712
<i>The second time,
the first time was in Los Angeles.</i>

616
00:48:57,052 --> 00:48:58,076
<i>I stand corrected.</i>

617
00:49:00,188 --> 00:49:04,955
<i>Mr, Landers, please call
Mr, Summers at his office.</i>

618
00:49:05,460 --> 00:49:08,190
<i>Mr, Summers for Mr, Landers.</i>

619
00:49:19,274 --> 00:49:21,071
- Landers.
- Mr. Summers.

620
00:49:21,143 --> 00:49:22,735
Glad you could get here so fast.

621
00:49:22,811 --> 00:49:24,676
- Well, you said...
- Right, have a seat.

622
00:49:24,746 --> 00:49:25,746
Thank you.

623
00:49:25,781 --> 00:49:27,840
- How's it going, Landers?
- Fine.

624
00:49:27,916 --> 00:49:31,750
- You took over while Slavic is vacationing?
- Yes, sir.

625
00:49:32,354 --> 00:49:35,983
- Think you can handle a store as manager?
- I'm sure I can.

626
00:49:36,058 --> 00:49:37,355
Good.

627
00:49:37,893 --> 00:49:40,225
- Everything all right at home?
- Wonderful.

628
00:49:40,295 --> 00:49:43,230
The missus? Kids? Adam? Betsy?

629
00:49:43,298 --> 00:49:44,356
Becky.

630
00:49:44,433 --> 00:49:48,802
Good, what is this "seeing God" crap
all about?

631
00:49:49,938 --> 00:49:52,998
It's not crap, Mr. Summers. I've seen him.

632
00:49:54,810 --> 00:49:57,142
I've heard it all in this chair.

633
00:49:58,980 --> 00:50:01,141
I know what being a manager
can do to a man.

634
00:50:01,950 --> 00:50:03,110
Trouble with books.

635
00:50:03,919 --> 00:50:06,945
- Humping check-out girls in the freezer.
- I'm only the assistant.

636
00:50:07,022 --> 00:50:08,455
You can tell me.

637
00:50:08,523 --> 00:50:11,788
There's nothing like that to tell.
I really have seen him.

638
00:50:13,328 --> 00:50:18,288
Landers, the founder and
principal stockholder of Food World...

639
00:50:19,267 --> 00:50:21,497
is a man devoted to prayer.

640
00:50:22,237 --> 00:50:26,105
Lowell Wilson has personally
gotten down on his knees...

641
00:50:26,975 --> 00:50:29,068
with three US Presidents.

642
00:50:29,144 --> 00:50:32,944
He attended prayer breakfasts
and asked for God's blessing...

643
00:50:33,215 --> 00:50:37,447
with the Joint Chiefs of Staff
right in the war room of the Pentagon.

644
00:50:39,054 --> 00:50:43,252
I don't think that Mr. Wilson
is going to take too kindly to the idea...

645
00:50:43,325 --> 00:50:45,589
that one of his employees...

646
00:50:46,228 --> 00:50:50,324
is claiming to have had a personal
audience with the Almighty himself.

647
00:50:50,499 --> 00:50:54,663
I should think that he would be very happy
to know that his prayers are heard.

648
00:50:54,736 --> 00:50:57,296
Mr. Wilson has reached
that point in his life...

649
00:50:57,372 --> 00:50:59,704
where he can be sure his prayers are heard.

650
00:50:59,775 --> 00:51:01,743
He doesn't need any help from you.

651
00:51:01,810 --> 00:51:04,904
It's not me. I'm just kind of like a Moses.

652
00:51:08,717 --> 00:51:10,344
Look, Landers.

653
00:51:11,419 --> 00:51:14,616
I don't want to pump any sunshine
up your skirt...

654
00:51:14,689 --> 00:51:18,625
but you have a future at Food World.
Don't blow it.

655
00:51:19,561 --> 00:51:23,588
Now, you just keep your mouth shut,
and stay away from reporters.

656
00:51:26,568 --> 00:51:27,967
And if I don't?

657
00:51:29,771 --> 00:51:32,968
God may have been interested in you
as an assistant manager...

658
00:51:33,041 --> 00:51:36,738
we'll just see how he feels
about you as a bag stuffer.

659
00:51:40,982 --> 00:51:42,279
Over here!

660
00:51:42,984 --> 00:51:45,612
I thought I'd straighten up a little.

661
00:51:46,688 --> 00:51:48,485
The mess people make.

662
00:51:49,524 --> 00:51:50,718
Take a seat.

663
00:51:52,761 --> 00:51:54,228
It's started?

664
00:51:55,130 --> 00:51:57,963
You said you saw me,
and the pressure started.

665
00:51:58,033 --> 00:52:01,298
- Is it going to get any worse?
- How should I know?

666
00:52:02,571 --> 00:52:04,505
What do you mean, how should you know?

667
00:52:04,573 --> 00:52:07,098
- How could I know?
- You know everything.

668
00:52:08,210 --> 00:52:09,768
I only know what is.

669
00:52:09,845 --> 00:52:14,441
Also, I'm very big on what was.
On what isn't yet, I haven't got a clue.

670
00:52:15,116 --> 00:52:17,209
- But when you said...
- Move your foot.

671
00:52:17,285 --> 00:52:18,547
Sit down.

672
00:52:19,054 --> 00:52:21,249
When you said everything would work out...

673
00:52:21,323 --> 00:52:23,188
I thought you could tell the future.

674
00:52:23,258 --> 00:52:27,160
Absolutely, I could tell the future,
the minute it becomes the past.

675
00:52:27,229 --> 00:52:31,097
I said, everything could work out,
if that's everybody's choice.

676
00:52:31,299 --> 00:52:34,325
People have to decide
what's to be done with the world.

677
00:52:34,402 --> 00:52:37,496
I can't make a personal decision
for everybody.

678
00:52:38,540 --> 00:52:40,770
Why the face? So far, so good.

679
00:52:40,842 --> 00:52:44,175
We hit the papers, a little TV,
we're in business.

680
00:52:45,046 --> 00:52:47,037
I'm liable to lose my job.

681
00:52:47,949 --> 00:52:52,215
Lose a job, save a world. Not a bad deal.

682
00:52:58,059 --> 00:52:59,458
Hey, Adam.

683
00:53:08,203 --> 00:53:11,468
- What are you doing here?
- I got off early from work, Son.

684
00:53:11,539 --> 00:53:13,769
I thought I'd give you a lift home.

685
00:53:13,842 --> 00:53:15,833
No thanks, Dad. I'll walk.

686
00:53:16,912 --> 00:53:20,177
- Come on.
- No, I got new tennis shoes on.

687
00:53:20,682 --> 00:53:22,513
I want to break them in.

688
00:53:23,518 --> 00:53:25,076
See you later.

689
00:53:26,755 --> 00:53:28,552
Come on, let's go.

690
00:53:47,642 --> 00:53:49,405
<i>Why wouldn't they be embarrassed?</i>

691
00:53:49,844 --> 00:53:53,575
- Their friends ribbed the hell out of them.
- That's rotten.

692
00:53:54,015 --> 00:53:57,644
They wanted to know if you could
get their test answers from God.

693
00:53:57,719 --> 00:54:00,745
And could he do anything
about their little-league team?

694
00:54:00,822 --> 00:54:03,290
They gave them a very rough day.

695
00:54:03,358 --> 00:54:06,418
Jerry, what are you going to do
about Mr. Summers?

696
00:54:06,995 --> 00:54:09,361
What can I do?
What do you want me to do?

697
00:54:09,998 --> 00:54:13,525
I want you to say no more about it,
like he said not to.

698
00:54:14,769 --> 00:54:18,466
Bobbie,
Mr. Summers represents Food World.

699
00:54:18,873 --> 00:54:22,832
God is with "World World."
It's a slightly bigger obligation.

700
00:54:23,411 --> 00:54:26,869
- Bigger than your job?
- I have no choice.

701
00:54:27,248 --> 00:54:28,806
That's the problem.

702
00:54:28,883 --> 00:54:30,783
The problem is, you do!

703
00:54:31,419 --> 00:54:34,786
How far do you intend to take this?
How long is this going to go on?

704
00:54:34,856 --> 00:54:39,850
Until everyone gets the message.
Until I can convince people of this miracle.

705
00:54:40,428 --> 00:54:41,861
I mean, that's what it is.

706
00:54:41,930 --> 00:54:43,795
It's a miracle, nothing less.

707
00:54:43,865 --> 00:54:47,460
I have to reach the greatest number
of people possible and tell them.

708
00:54:47,535 --> 00:54:50,766
It's for you.
The producer of <i>The Dinah Shore Show</i>.

709
00:54:51,439 --> 00:54:55,671
You've been on television a long...
Not that long. I'm sorry.

710
00:54:55,744 --> 00:54:58,144
No, I'm much younger than I look.

711
00:54:58,813 --> 00:55:01,646
- No, I didn't want to say it that way.
- You look...

712
00:55:01,716 --> 00:55:05,311
I'm younger than people think I am,
because I've been around a long time.

713
00:55:05,387 --> 00:55:07,855
Everything you've done
has had such tremendous impact.

714
00:55:07,922 --> 00:55:10,982
<i>It's been magnificent.
I've never done anything bad in my life.</i>

715
00:55:11,059 --> 00:55:12,458
<i>I'm one of the perfect people.</i>

716
00:55:12,527 --> 00:55:14,495
<i>- That's kind of exciting.
- It is.</i>

717
00:55:14,562 --> 00:55:16,792
<i>Do you remember your first moment
on television?</i>

718
00:55:16,865 --> 00:55:21,825
<i>Actually, I do, It was in 1948.
It was Maggie McNellis's Crystal Room.</i>

719
00:55:21,903 --> 00:55:24,064
<i>We were told to be visual in those days.</i>

720
00:55:24,139 --> 00:55:26,539
The Picture of Dorian Grey
<i>was very popular then.</i>

721
00:55:26,608 --> 00:55:29,941
<i>I gave a 15-second impression</i>
<i>of</i> The Picture of Dorian Grey,

722
00:55:30,011 --> 00:55:32,206
<i>About the man who carouses.</i>

723
00:55:32,447 --> 00:55:34,915
<i>He stays looking good,
but his picture falls apart.</i>

724
00:55:48,863 --> 00:55:51,093
- Ready, Mr. Landers?
- Right.

725
00:55:52,467 --> 00:55:54,401
<i>I think I broke a jaw.</i>

726
00:55:58,139 --> 00:56:00,334
America is not ready for this.

727
00:56:02,544 --> 00:56:05,604
Okay, you'll take the empty seat
next to Dinah.

728
00:56:05,947 --> 00:56:10,111
- This show is taped, isn't it?
- Yes, it'll be on a week from today.

729
00:56:10,552 --> 00:56:14,886
You may have read about my next guest
in the newspapers recently.

730
00:56:15,190 --> 00:56:19,320
He is a supermarket manager
from Tarzana, California...

731
00:56:19,594 --> 00:56:23,621
who says that he has been instructed
by God to spread the message...

732
00:56:23,698 --> 00:56:26,724
that God lives and God cares.

733
00:56:27,368 --> 00:56:29,734
Please welcome Mr. Jerry Landers.

734
00:56:33,341 --> 00:56:36,276
- Am I on?
- Almost, that applause is for you.

735
00:56:38,847 --> 00:56:41,577
- Is Dinah nice, Daddy?
- Not now, honey.

736
00:56:42,250 --> 00:56:44,650
<i>- You're not nervous, are you?
- No.</i>

737
00:56:46,588 --> 00:56:50,820
<i>I don't mind telling you, I am.
You have some pretty powerful friend.</i>

738
00:56:53,128 --> 00:56:55,528
- Why are they laughing?
- Just watch.

739
00:56:56,064 --> 00:56:58,123
Because God is Daddy's friend.

740
00:56:59,334 --> 00:57:03,964
<i>- Why do you suppose he picked you, Jerry?
- God only knows, I mean...</i>

741
00:57:06,141 --> 00:57:07,403
<i>You're right.</i>

742
00:57:07,475 --> 00:57:12,139
<i>You said that God wants us to know
that he still cares.</i>

743
00:57:12,514 --> 00:57:15,347
<i>Is there anything else
that he wants us to know?</i>

744
00:57:15,416 --> 00:57:19,113
<i>Yes, that he's given us everything
that we need to make our life work...</i>

745
00:57:19,187 --> 00:57:21,519
<i>make the world work,
and that he's watching us.</i>

746
00:57:21,589 --> 00:57:23,580
<i>- He's watching?
- Yes.</i>

747
00:57:23,658 --> 00:57:25,091
<i>Watching us?</i>

748
00:57:25,994 --> 00:57:27,393
<i>- Now?
- Yes.</i>

749
00:57:32,834 --> 00:57:36,895
<i>You agreed earlier
to be part of an experiment today...</i>

750
00:57:37,438 --> 00:57:39,838
<i>with the Los Angeles Police Department.</i>

751
00:57:39,908 --> 00:57:41,967
<i>Do you want me to take a lie detector test?</i>

752
00:57:42,043 --> 00:57:43,772
<i>- No.
- I will.</i>

753
00:57:44,646 --> 00:57:48,980
<i>What this is, is a sketch artist
from the Los Angeles Police Department.</i>

754
00:57:49,284 --> 00:57:53,812
<i>He's an expert and very adept
at making a sketch from a description.</i>

755
00:57:53,888 --> 00:57:57,915
<i>I think all of us here would like to know
what God looks like.</i>

756
00:57:57,992 --> 00:57:59,550
<i>You would like to know.</i>

757
00:58:03,831 --> 00:58:05,093
<i>- Shall we?
- Okay.</i>

758
00:58:05,166 --> 00:58:06,599
<i>Follow me.</i>

759
00:58:07,535 --> 00:58:11,164
<i>- Jerry, this is Mr, Fernando Ponce.
- Hello, sir.</i>

760
00:58:11,239 --> 00:58:13,002
<i>- Please sit there.
- Thank you.</i>

761
00:58:13,408 --> 00:58:18,311
<i>Mr, Ponce, as I said, is an expert
at eyewitness sketches...</i>

762
00:58:18,513 --> 00:58:20,504
<i>for the LA Police Department.</i>

763
00:58:22,951 --> 00:58:25,749
<i>- How do I start?
- Tell me about the shape of his face.</i>

764
00:58:26,187 --> 00:58:27,882
<i>The shape is...</i>

765
00:58:29,557 --> 00:58:31,081
<i>triangular.</i>

766
00:58:31,526 --> 00:58:32,652
<i>- Good.
- I guess.</i>

767
00:58:33,995 --> 00:58:37,556
<i>- He's got large ears.
- He has?</i>

768
00:58:37,632 --> 00:58:40,430
Jerry, I don't believe you actually did this.

769
00:58:40,501 --> 00:58:41,991
It was their idea.

770
00:58:42,103 --> 00:58:44,230
<i>He does, He wears glasses.</i>

771
00:58:45,373 --> 00:58:47,034
<i>God wears glasses?</i>

772
00:58:49,510 --> 00:58:51,569
<i>He's wearing a fishing cap.</i>

773
00:58:52,280 --> 00:58:55,249
<i>- A fishing cap?
- Maybe it's like a baseball cap.</i>

774
00:58:55,383 --> 00:58:58,477
<i>His lips are kind of thin.
His nose is straight.</i>

775
00:59:00,088 --> 00:59:01,953
<i>It's round on the ends.</i>

776
00:59:02,023 --> 00:59:04,082
No one's supposed to know
what God looks like.

777
00:59:04,158 --> 00:59:05,716
- I do.
- You do?

778
00:59:06,160 --> 00:59:09,687
Yeah. In <i>Bible Comics,</i>
they had a picture of him last week.

779
00:59:10,265 --> 00:59:14,759
<i>They're horn-rimmed glasses.
They're plastic ones, you know?</i>

780
00:59:14,836 --> 00:59:17,999
<i>Where would you suppose
he would get his glasses?</i>

781
00:59:20,074 --> 00:59:21,598
<i>I don't know.</i>

782
00:59:23,378 --> 00:59:25,437
<i>- Anywhere he likes.
- Yeah.</i>

783
00:59:27,515 --> 00:59:30,882
Boy, I sure hope my friends are
doing their homework.

784
00:59:31,486 --> 00:59:34,683
<i>This is what God looked like to you?</i>

785
00:59:35,723 --> 00:59:38,283
<i>He's sort of captured the sense...</i>

786
00:59:39,327 --> 00:59:40,521
<i>I guess.</i>

787
00:59:41,362 --> 00:59:43,956
<i>America, here it is...</i>

788
00:59:44,399 --> 00:59:48,165
<i>as seen through the eyes of Jerry Landers.</i>

789
00:59:48,236 --> 00:59:49,294
<i>God.</i>

790
01:00:01,616 --> 01:00:04,107
Dad, you're going to get God arrested.

791
01:00:06,654 --> 01:00:10,852
- You said it would be done by 6:00.
- I'm sorry, but I just got the part.

792
01:00:13,961 --> 01:00:17,021
- Weren't you on the <i>Dinah Show</i> last night?
- Yeah.

793
01:00:17,799 --> 01:00:20,563
Yeah, that was real different.

794
01:00:22,036 --> 01:00:23,230
Excuse me.

795
01:00:23,404 --> 01:00:25,634
How am I supposed to get home now?

796
01:00:25,940 --> 01:00:27,134
Where to, mister?

797
01:00:32,513 --> 01:00:33,741
Get in.

798
01:00:46,294 --> 01:00:48,387
I hope you have a license.

799
01:00:56,137 --> 01:00:59,834
- Did you watch <i>Dinah Shore</i> last night?
- I watch everything.

800
01:01:00,775 --> 01:01:03,938
I got you national exposure.
I hope you're happy.

801
01:01:04,712 --> 01:01:06,441
I could be happier.

802
01:01:07,382 --> 01:01:08,474
How?

803
01:01:08,549 --> 01:01:10,312
For starters, you do a show like that...

804
01:01:10,385 --> 01:01:12,910
you don't let them put you on
the last few minutes.

805
01:01:12,987 --> 01:01:15,012
That's for fellas who write diet books.

806
01:01:15,089 --> 01:01:16,818
It wasn't up to me.

807
01:01:17,625 --> 01:01:19,490
And what was that drawing thing?

808
01:01:19,560 --> 01:01:22,427
- He was a police artist.
- Man draws crooks.

809
01:01:23,131 --> 01:01:27,727
Makes everybody look like a crook.
Made me look like a second-story man.

810
01:01:28,403 --> 01:01:32,066
- It's publicity.
- I'm used to a little better treatment.

811
01:01:32,740 --> 01:01:37,143
That painting of me by Michelangelo,
that's a picture.

812
01:01:38,112 --> 01:01:40,103
And he did it laying flat on his back.

813
01:01:41,082 --> 01:01:42,310
Now what happens?

814
01:01:42,383 --> 01:01:46,979
Now we see who can still believe,
who wants to, who needs to.

815
01:01:47,622 --> 01:01:50,147
A few million people
saw you last night, right?

816
01:01:50,224 --> 01:01:52,624
A few million?
Some of them will believe you.

817
01:01:52,693 --> 01:01:55,389
Some are going to want to
punch me in the head.

818
01:01:55,463 --> 01:01:57,397
Some will want to fire me.

819
01:01:57,465 --> 01:01:59,797
Some may decide I'm too crazy to live with.

820
01:01:59,867 --> 01:02:02,961
We can't worry about those.
The ball is rolling.

821
01:02:03,171 --> 01:02:07,301
- Yeah, right over me.
- Don't be a malcontent, I'll watch over you.

822
01:02:07,375 --> 01:02:10,469
While you're watching over me,
would you mind watching the road?

823
01:02:10,545 --> 01:02:12,274
I'd rather watch a nice sunset.

824
01:02:25,960 --> 01:02:28,724
<i>Dinah Shore</i> must get a pretty big rating.

825
01:02:35,403 --> 01:02:37,030
You're on, kid.

826
01:02:48,583 --> 01:02:50,813
- Jerry?
- Yes, God?

827
01:02:51,018 --> 01:02:54,010
You have the strength
that comes from knowing.

828
01:03:21,148 --> 01:03:24,606
Can I have one minute with you?
I have something very important to say.

829
01:03:24,685 --> 01:03:25,947
It just can't wait.

830
01:03:26,020 --> 01:03:28,488
Please, bless my baby.

831
01:03:29,590 --> 01:03:32,684
Touch him, pray for him. Pray for my baby.

832
01:03:32,760 --> 01:03:35,558
If I could just have one second with you...

833
01:03:36,664 --> 01:03:39,155
- It's not for me, it's for you.
- Sanctify my body.

834
01:03:39,233 --> 01:03:41,394
Bless him, make him a true believer!

835
01:03:41,469 --> 01:03:44,165
I have something very important.
This is for you!

836
01:03:44,238 --> 01:03:46,729
- Give me your golden staff.
- I can't!

837
01:03:47,408 --> 01:03:51,367
- God said it's okay.
- I'll tell you this, it's very important!

838
01:03:51,512 --> 01:03:54,072
Officer, could you move
the rest of them along?

839
01:03:54,148 --> 01:03:55,410
Yes, sir.

840
01:03:56,551 --> 01:03:59,179
One little moment, please.
What I have to tell him is...

841
01:03:59,253 --> 01:04:00,253
Okay.

842
01:04:00,621 --> 01:04:03,613
I went to empty the garbage,
and two people blessed me.

843
01:04:03,691 --> 01:04:05,886
Then one of them blessed the garbage.

844
01:04:05,960 --> 01:04:09,521
And then he asked me if our children
were conceived immaculately.

845
01:04:09,597 --> 01:04:10,928
Now, calm down, honey.

846
01:04:10,998 --> 01:04:13,159
The police had to take our kids
to school today.

847
01:04:13,234 --> 01:04:15,794
- They said it was safer.
- That's awful!

848
01:04:16,003 --> 01:04:18,494
Yes, that's awful.
You want to hear awfuller?

849
01:04:18,573 --> 01:04:21,064
Mr. Summers said that Lowell Wilson...

850
01:04:21,142 --> 01:04:25,203
is personally deciding
whether or not you can keep your job.

851
01:04:25,613 --> 01:04:27,274
Is that awful enough for you?

852
01:04:27,348 --> 01:04:29,441
Now, Bobbie, don't let it get to you.

853
01:04:29,517 --> 01:04:31,144
Don't let it get to me?

854
01:04:32,787 --> 01:04:35,449
Jerry, it's gotten to me! Don't you see?

855
01:04:36,190 --> 01:04:39,284
Jerry, look, you've got him to talk to.

856
01:04:39,360 --> 01:04:43,660
It's just me here,
me and those religious nuts outside!

857
01:04:44,465 --> 01:04:46,456
I have to leave the phone off the hook.

858
01:04:46,534 --> 01:04:49,799
People keep calling up
and asking to talk to God.

859
01:04:50,104 --> 01:04:54,165
Except, of course, for the guy
who offered to chew on my pantyhose!

860
01:04:55,977 --> 01:04:59,743
Telegrams, notes in the mail box
and the doorways.

861
01:05:00,348 --> 01:05:02,816
Today they even put one in the dog's mouth.

862
01:05:02,883 --> 01:05:04,282
This is from the university.

863
01:05:04,352 --> 01:05:06,946
I've been invited to appear
before a theology group.

864
01:05:07,021 --> 01:05:09,819
<i>- They want to verify the miracle.
- Terrific.</i>

865
01:05:09,924 --> 01:05:14,122
<i>It is! This'll give me credibility,
and God'll get his word across.</i>

866
01:05:14,195 --> 01:05:15,753
<i>It'll help me keep my job.</i>

867
01:05:16,998 --> 01:05:20,229
Mr. Landers,
it is the consensus of this group...

868
01:05:21,002 --> 01:05:25,996
that you are a person of
little or no theological knowledge.

869
01:05:26,874 --> 01:05:29,434
You have demonstrated, over the years...

870
01:05:29,510 --> 01:05:33,810
an astonishing lack of interest
in spiritual matters.

871
01:05:35,049 --> 01:05:39,679
It strikes me,
as one who has actually heard his voice...

872
01:05:40,554 --> 01:05:45,548
that you have virtually no prerequisites
to make direct contact...

873
01:05:45,626 --> 01:05:48,686
- with the Almighty, whatsoever.
- You've heard him?

874
01:05:50,798 --> 01:05:53,096
He has made his word known to me.

875
01:05:53,167 --> 01:05:54,498
What was he wearing?

876
01:05:55,269 --> 01:05:57,601
I know his word through the scriptures.

877
01:05:57,672 --> 01:05:59,936
It would be blasphemy to suggest...

878
01:06:00,007 --> 01:06:02,908
that we could describe the Creator
in human terms.

879
01:06:02,977 --> 01:06:04,103
Why?

880
01:06:04,178 --> 01:06:05,702
If He created us...

881
01:06:05,780 --> 01:06:10,581
why wouldn't he appear to us as one of us?

882
01:06:10,651 --> 01:06:11,651
Don't you...

883
01:06:19,326 --> 01:06:21,260
Don't you, young man...

884
01:06:21,862 --> 01:06:25,457
try to teach this assemblage
the role of the Deity.

885
01:06:27,835 --> 01:06:31,134
Rabbi Silverstone,
my good and great friend...

886
01:06:31,205 --> 01:06:35,574
brother in the work of the Lord, with
whom we have broke bread many times...

887
01:06:35,643 --> 01:06:38,407
is a pillar of the American Jew community.

888
01:06:39,980 --> 01:06:43,677
Bishop Reardon represents millions
of Roman Catholics.

889
01:06:44,485 --> 01:06:48,080
Bishop Marcos,
multitudes of Greek Orthodoxers.

890
01:06:48,856 --> 01:06:52,087
Why, we have virtually every
religious persuasion...

891
01:06:52,159 --> 01:06:53,717
represented here today.

892
01:06:53,794 --> 01:06:56,695
And I personally have been chosen...

893
01:06:56,764 --> 01:06:59,892
to render the benediction
at this year's Super Bowl.

894
01:07:02,536 --> 01:07:07,496
Mr. Landers, we really find
insufficient documentation...

895
01:07:08,142 --> 01:07:09,803
to support your claim.

896
01:07:09,877 --> 01:07:11,845
But you're not saying it didn't happen.

897
01:07:11,912 --> 01:07:15,575
No, we are saying
there is insufficient documentation.

898
01:07:15,649 --> 01:07:20,143
Which puts the score at God 7, you 0.

899
01:07:21,589 --> 01:07:24,524
We have decided, however,
out of a sense of fairness...

900
01:07:24,592 --> 01:07:27,152
and ecclesiastical curiosity...

901
01:07:27,495 --> 01:07:31,363
to allow you to present us
with certain evidence.

902
01:07:32,099 --> 01:07:33,396
What evidence?

903
01:07:33,467 --> 01:07:36,231
We have assembled a set of questions...

904
01:07:37,371 --> 01:07:39,805
for you to ask God.

905
01:07:40,775 --> 01:07:42,675
There are 50 questions.

906
01:07:44,211 --> 01:07:45,508
Fifty.

907
01:07:46,614 --> 01:07:49,139
You want me to get God to take a quiz?

908
01:07:49,216 --> 01:07:51,650
Unless you've been concealing
an abundant knowledge...

909
01:07:51,719 --> 01:07:53,846
Which I find highly doubtful.

910
01:07:53,921 --> 01:07:57,721
There are questions there
that you could not possibly answer.

911
01:07:59,527 --> 01:08:02,428
Look, I don't know when...

912
01:08:02,830 --> 01:08:04,821
or if he'll ever appear again.

913
01:08:04,899 --> 01:08:09,427
As a control measure, you will remain
locked in your hotel room...

914
01:08:09,804 --> 01:08:11,271
alone.

915
01:08:12,873 --> 01:08:14,773
- Not even my wife?
- No.

916
01:08:14,842 --> 01:08:17,367
There'll be no outside calls, whatsoever.

917
01:08:19,246 --> 01:08:21,180
You could, of course, decline.

918
01:08:21,248 --> 01:08:24,445
But then,
that would form the basis of our report.

919
01:08:34,428 --> 01:08:35,588
God?

920
01:08:53,214 --> 01:08:55,182
- God?
- Room service.

921
01:09:02,823 --> 01:09:05,018
Just put it right around over here, please.

922
01:09:07,561 --> 01:09:10,052
You can't come in. I understand.

923
01:09:10,931 --> 01:09:12,831
Do I need to sign this?

924
01:09:15,736 --> 01:09:17,567
Thank you very much.

925
01:09:31,685 --> 01:09:34,449
- They forgot the ketchup.
- Come in!

926
01:09:35,256 --> 01:09:37,281
They're playing our number.

927
01:09:47,034 --> 01:09:50,299
$11 for a steak? Who would have thought?

928
01:09:50,504 --> 01:09:54,565
With me, cows were an afterthought.
Just to give new mothers a little rest.

929
01:09:56,644 --> 01:09:59,772
- Boy, am I glad to see you.
- Eat. It'll get cold.

930
01:10:05,486 --> 01:10:06,612
Pretty cute.

931
01:10:07,187 --> 01:10:10,179
- What is it?
- They made sure you couldn't answer.

932
01:10:10,257 --> 01:10:12,851
The questions are in the ancient tongue
of Aramaic.

933
01:10:12,927 --> 01:10:14,656
Is that what that is?

934
01:10:15,162 --> 01:10:19,724
They've figured out so many ways to talk
to each other, they're finding nobody can.

935
01:10:20,334 --> 01:10:24,236
Let's see.
"What's the true origin of the universe?

936
01:10:25,439 --> 01:10:30,433
"What is the source of the planet Earth?"
